title: For Sale:  WEBLEY MARK V REVOLVER
postcontent:
Here is the nicest Webley Mark V revolver you will ever see.  The mark V is one of the least common of the big Webley top-breaks, as it had a very short production run.  It was introduced in 1913 and superseded by the big Mark VI in 1915: most Mark V’s date from 1914-15.  Thus nearly all of them would have seen service in World War One, and many were issued during World War Two as well.
I bought this revolver as a college student in 1966.  It was imported as military surplus in the halcyon years before the never-sufficiently-to-be-cursed Gun Control Act of 1968, so of course it has absolutely no importer markings.  It has British military AND commercial proof marks.  These were required by British law whenever a gun was released from Crown ownership into the commercial market.  There is a British “sold-out-of-service mark” (opposed Broad Arrows). It is stamped with the country of origin, “ENGLAND,” a requirement of US law for imported goods since 1890.
The serial numbers on the frame and barrel do not match, but because there are both military and commercial proof markings, it left England that way.  It was almost certainly assembled using parts of two different existing revolvers, probably at the beginning of World War Two.  In 1939 the British were caught short on armaments and arsenal rebuilding of older weapons was a standard practice while production lines ramped up.  It has been very professionally refinished, and the job is so well done that all of the markings are intact and undamaged.
The 4” barrel has a bright, shiny bore; the cylinder chambers are unmarked by rust or corrosion.  It is TIGHT, much tighter than most Webleys.  Lockup is solid and it is fully shootable.  Functioning is perfect in both single and double action.  The cylinder—as is true of nearly all Webleys in the USA—has been modified to accept .45 Auto with half-moon clips, and four of these are included in the sale.  It will also shoot .45 Auto Rim, if you can find any.
I have reached an age when I’m “thinning the herd” and selling off much of my collection: for re-enactors, gun collectors, and tin-can-bouncers, this gun is ideal.  It’s a chance to get a fairly uncommon gun at a reasonable price; one you can actually shoot for fun or self-defense.  Nobody ever made better revolvers than Webley, and this is a very, very good one.You will pay ACTUAL SHIPPING, to a US street address, via FEDEX.  I cannot send a handgun through the US Mails, and FEDEX cannot deliver to PO Boxes.   BE CERTAIN YOUR FFL HOLDER WILL ACCEPT THIS GUN FROM A PRIVATE INDIVIDUAL.  I will include a courtesy copy of my driver's license for his records.  Bona fide Virginia residents age 21 and over can purchase it in a face to face transfer with proof of residence.PLEASE NOTE THE FOLLOWING CAREFULLY!NO SALES TO CALIFORNIA, NEW YORK, NEW JERSEY, OR MASSACHUSETTS! I recently had a supposed "buyer" for this gun who wanted to engage in a shady transaction.  I won't go into details, but this fellow ended up being reported to the BATF and the FBI for attempted illegal purchase, forgery, and mail fraud.  Believe me, folks: I know the laws on this sort of sale inside out and backwards and I WILL spot you if you try to scam me or get me to do something illegal.  I WILL report you to Armslist, and the Federal authorities if you try.
